gomodel:SYNGO_4959  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: In this paper, the authors demonstrate impairment of short-term and long-term plasticity in synaptogyrin/synaptophysin double knockout (DKO) mice (Fig. 5C; Fig. 6C, Fig. 7 C-D):\nNo changes in basal synaptic transmission were observed: CA3->CA1 EPSPs and paired-pulse facilitation (PPF) at all interpulse intervals, providing no evidence for a role of these proteins in exocytosis (but see PMID: 31090538)\n\nHowever, the study reveals significant impairment of short-term plasticity in DKO (Fig. 5C). Furthermore, posttetanic potentiation (PTP) in DKO and synaptogyrin 1 single KO is reduced by 50% (Fig. 6C), suggesting involvement in physiological PTP induction. Moreover, long-term plasticity (LTP) in response to tetanic field stimulation of Shaeffer collateral pathway is significantly reduced (Fig. 7). In order to exclude LTP impairment as a secondary consequence of reduced PTP, LTP is measured in voltage-pairing protocol, which confirms the observation.\n\nThus, this data suggests involvement of synaptogyrin 1 in modulation of chemical synaptic transmission by an unknown mechanism.. Experimental description: Materials and Methods:\nGeneration of Knockout Mice\n\nElectrophysiological Recordings\nHippocampal slices (250-300 m) were prepared from 8- to 14- week-old control and mutant mice" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2023-02-02" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4959" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

